refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.description;
public stringSplFileObject::fgetss stringallowable_tags
Identical to SplFileObject::fgets, except that SplFileObject::fgetss attempts to strip any HTML and PHP tags from the text it reads.

&reftitle.parameters;
allowable_tags
You can use the optional third parameter to specify tags which should not be stripped.

&reftitle.returnvalues;


 Returns a string containing the next line of the file with HTML and PHP
 code stripped, or &false; on error.

  &reftitle.examples;



    SplFileObject::fgetss example


<?php
$str = <<<EOD
<html><body>
 <p>Welcome! Today is the <?php echo(date('jS')); ?> of <?= date('F'); ?>.</p>
</body></html>
Text outside of the HTML block.
EOD;
file_put_contents("sample.php", $str);

$file = new SplFileObject("sample.php");
while (!$file->eof()) {
    echo $file->fgetss();
}
?>


